From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Christopher Ayers <brianboitano87@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 2 Jul 2026 09:06:19 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 2/4] nvmoe: expert cache pools on the layer's device (GPU
 stage)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Pool tensors now live in the buffer type of the device that runs their
layer: full offload puts them in VRAM, partial offload splits pool
groups per device (grouping key = geometry + buffer type). The fetch
path is unchanged logic through the backend API — one O_DIRECT pread
into the bounce buffer, then ggml_backend_tensor_set per matrix kind,
which is a memcpy on CPU pools and a synchronous H2D copy on device
pools. When any pool is on a GPU the bounce buffer is allocated from
the device's host buffer type (pinned), so the H2D copies are straight
DMA and O_DIRECT still accepts the pages. No CUDA API appears in the
runtime; the same code serves every backend.

Gate results on the CUDA backend (RTX 5070 Ti, CUDA 12.8, sm_120),
stock GGUF vs pack, llama-nvmoe-logits + compare_logits.py:

  OLMoE-1B-7B  -ngl 99  all resident            BIT-IDENTICAL (32 steps)
  OLMoE-1B-7B  -ngl 99  NVMOE_CACHE_MB=512      BIT-IDENTICAL (34% hit,
                                                heavy eviction via VRAM)
  OLMoE-1B-7B  -ngl 8   CPU+CUDA pools mixed    BIT-IDENTICAL

CPU-only regression re-passed after the refactor. Fetch of 2.4GB of
cold experts into VRAM took 0.63s (~3.8GB/s through the pinned bounce
at QD1) vs 1.7s for the CPU memcpy path.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
